<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1900-10-23T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1900-10-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="449" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d449">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Lord <persName type="from">Pauncefote</persName>
                                    to Mr. <persName type="to">Hay</persName>.</hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">British Embassy</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Newport, R.
                                            I.</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1900-10-23"><hi rend="italic">October 23,
                                        1900</hi></date>.</dateline>
                                <seg rendition="#left">No. 315.]</seg></opener>
                            <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: In pursuance of instructions which I
                                have received from Her Majesty’s principal secretary of state for
                                foreign affairs, I have the honor to communicate to you the text of
                                an agreement between Great Britain and Germany relating to the
                                present trouble in China, which was signed in London on the 16th
                                instant by the Marquis of Salisbury and the German ambassador on
                                behalf of their respective Governments, and to invite the acceptance
                                by the United States of the principles recorded in that
                                agreement.</p>
                            <p>I have, etc.,</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Pauncefote.</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>